<section class="card">
  <h2>What Buttercrunch Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Buttercrunch is best for gardeners who want tender butterhead lettuce with a compact head and good fresh eating quality.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is more about quality than heat-proof summer production. Plant it in cool windows and harvest before heat pushes it past its best stage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Buttercrunch Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Lettuce is a strong short-season crop because it grows in cool weather and can be harvested before full maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    The bigger challenge is heat. Warm weather can make lettuce bolt, turn bitter, or lose quality quickly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short-season gardeners can often grow lettuce in spring and again in late summer or fall, depending on local frost timing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Buttercrunch</h2>

  <p>
    Plant lettuce early in spring once soil can be worked, either by direct sowing or transplanting. Transplants give a faster start for head or bibb types.
  </p>

  <p>
    For fall lettuce, sow or transplant late enough to avoid the worst heat but early enough to grow before hard freezes.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/lettuce/">lettuce growing guide</a> and your frost dates. Lettuce timing is mostly about cool quality windows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Buttercrunch</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use cool windows:</strong> Lettuce quality is best before heat stress builds.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep moisture even:</strong> Dry soil can increase bitterness and slow growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Thin for the harvest type:</strong> Loose-leaf harvests can be tighter than full heads.</li>
    <li><strong>Use shade in warm spells:</strong> Afternoon shade or shade cloth can extend quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Harvest promptly:</strong> Mature lettuce can decline quickly in heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Succession sow:</strong> Small repeat sowings give steadier salads than one large planting.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Use</h2>

  <p>
    Harvest lettuce as baby leaves, individual outer leaves, or full heads depending on the variety and spacing.
  </p>

  <p>
    For cut-and-come-again harvests, cut above the growing point so plants can regrow. For heads, harvest when they are full but before heat or bolting ruins quality.
  </p>

  <p>
    Wash and cool lettuce soon after harvest. Lettuce is at its best when picked in the cool part of the day.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Buttercrunch</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting too late in spring:</strong> Heat can ruin quality before heads finish.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting soil dry out:</strong> Moisture stress can make lettuce bitter or slow.</li>
    <li><strong>Crowding head lettuce:</strong> Heads need more space than baby greens.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring warm spells:</strong> A few hot days can push lettuce toward bolting.</li>
    <li><strong>Waiting for perfect grocery-store heads:</strong> Home lettuce is often better harvested when quality is high, not when size is maximal.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Buttercrunch vs Other Lettuce Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with other lettuce varieties, Buttercrunch should be chosen for heat tolerance, head type, texture, and harvest style. Loose-leaf, romaine, crisphead, and butterhead lettuces solve different garden needs.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this crop, the better choice depends on what you want from the harvest. Buttercrunch is worth growing when its maturity window, plant habit, and kitchen use match your garden better than a faster, larger, or more specialized alternative.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Buttercrunch?</h2>

  <p>
    Buttercrunch is a good choice if you want fresh salads from a crop that can use cool parts of the season.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is less useful if you only have hot summer beds and no way to shade, water, or time the planting around heat.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>

  <p>
    Buttercrunch can be a good choice when the timing matches your spring conditions, growing season length, and expected fall frost. The exact planting window still depends on where you garden.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before choosing a planting date, check your local frost window and crop timing. A variety can fit short seasons well and still underperform if it is planted too late, started too late indoors, or grown in poor conditions.
  </p>

